<dl id="n08091d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08091d">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08091d"> 91(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> fatherly / silken / fishlike / burdensome / fruitful / flowery / girlish <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n08091d"><li>FW 562.04f </li><li><a href="../../flex/s/lexs.htm#n08091d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/s/l39s.htm#n08091d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n08091d">MS BL 47485-31</ms> </li><li>JJA 60:259 <a name="sd2" href="../../ff/fdra/sda.htm#sd2">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/s/sd2.htm#n08091d">Draft: III&sect;4.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[T]</font>he English language &hellip; has quite a number of endings by which to turn substantives into adjectives: <i>-en</i> (silken), <i>-y</i> (flowery), <i>-ish</i> (girlish), <i>-ly</i> (fatherly), <i>-like</i> (fishlike), <i>-some</i> (burdensome), <i>-ful</i> (sinful), and these might easily have been utilized still more than they actually have been. In point of fact, we possess not a few native adjectives by the side of more learned ones, e.g.<i>fatherly</i>: <i>paternal</i> <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 130</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
